(754, 'US8909824', 'Current methods for managing data blocks of fragments require the use of two timers for each data block or fragments. As defined by IEEE 802.16, the maximum number of fragments in the transmission window for a CID connection is 1024. Therefore, the maximum number of timers needed for transmission is 2*1024 for each CID connection. The number of timers required for even few CID connections is therefore very large. Using existing methods, the operating system has to be prepared to reserve a significant amount of its resource for the timers and their operations.', 'The invention provides a receiver for processing data fragments received from a transmitter using a single timer for connection between the receiver and the transmitter. The receiver minimizes the number of timers needed for management of data fragments, and hence lowers the memory and operating requirements of the operating system in processing the data fragments. The receiver include one module that process the fragments according to a processing index, which is part of each of the fragments, and facilitate sequential processing of fragments by the receiver, till one or more predefined conditions is met. The predefined conditions is said to be met, if the timer assigned to the each of the fragments is timed out or an acknowledgement of at least one of the data blocks in the each of the fragments is received. The receiver include a second module that start the timer assigned to the each of the fragments, where the timer runs until said processing of the each of the fragments is terminated, and the timer is then reassigned to a next one of the fragments before the next one of the fragments is processed. The timer has a timeout value, which depending on a life of the each of the fragments and time parameter thereof. The receiver also includes another module for inserting identifying information of the each of the fragments in a node of a timer management chain, inserting the identifying information of a next fragment in a next node of the timer management chain when a next fragment is received, and removing the node, having the identifying information for the fragment with the assigned timer, from the timer management chain and assigning the timer to the next fragment in next node when one or more pre-defined condition is met.', 'Management of transmitted or received data fragments in protocols such as WiMax and LTE.', 'Products and systems complying with LTE, including:<br />\nMobile Stations<br />\nCell Phones<br />\nPCMCIA Card<br />\n  USB Dongle<br />\n  Wireless Modules/ Chips                                                                  <br />\n  Wireless NIC  <br />\n  Wireless Sensors <br />\n  NFC Devices<br />\n  Wireless Adapter<br />\n  Personal Navigation Devices<br />\n  Consumer Appliances<br />\nIntermediate Devices:<br />\nAccess Nodes, <br />\nModems, <br />\nRouters, <br />\nCellular Repeaters, <br />\nCustomer Premise Equipments (CPE), <br />\nInternet Hotspots:BACK-END DEVICES<br />\n  Remote Radio Unit (RRU)<br />\n  Base Transceiver System (BTS)<br />\n  Base Station Controller (BSC)<br />\n  Mobile Switching Center (MSC)<br />\n  Radio Network Controller (RNC)<br />\n  Gateway Node<br />\n  Wireless Backhaul  Mobile Switching Center (MSC)<br />\n  Radio Network Controller (RNC)<br />\n  Gateway Node<br />\n  Wireless Backhaul', 'Broadcom<br />\nQualcomm<br />\nFujitsu<br />\nMotorola<br />\nZTE<br />\nErricsson<br />\nHuawei<br />\nAlcatel-Lucent<br />\nAT&T<br />\nMediaTek (Inprocomm, Ralink)<br />\nTexas Instruments<br />\nIntel Corporation<br />\nHTC Corporation<br />\nToshiba Corporation<br />\nSamsung<br />\nHitachi<br />\nMitsubishi<br />\nHoneywell<br />\nIntel (Acquired Envara, Lantiq ) <br />\nEmulex<br />\nMellanox<br />\nAllied Telesis<br />\nSTMicroelectronics <br />\nWipro-NewLogic<br />\nLG Electronics<br />\nRealtek<br />\nLattice (Acquired Silicon Image )<br />\nInfineon (Acquired AMDtek,CPE business from T