(863, 'US7557524', 'Existing architectures require illumination sources to be replaced manually when they break down, and therefore maintainance of such lighting devices becomes expensive and time-consuming. Maintinance of illumination at desired levels using existing devices is therefore inefficient, and existing devices do not enable remote monitoring and controlling of lighting devices that have LEDs.', 'The present invention maintains luminosity of a lighting device at a desired level by, at predetermined intervals, transferring an appropriate number of illumination groups between energized (ON) and non-energized light (OFF) emitting states. The present invention therefore, at periodic intervals, using a network coupled controller, evaluates (using test LEDs) whether the lighting device (having multiple illumination groups, each group having a plurality of LEDs) gives desired luminosity level, and if not, the controller energizes one or more groups to ensure that the illumination is at the desired level.', 'The technology relates to a lighting device having one or more light emitting diodes (LEDs) and having control means for luminous intensity measurement and maintenance', 'Lightning devices and Luminaires<br />\nControl/Lighting devices for Controlling/Maintaining LED illumination', 'Philips<br />\nNYX Hemera<br />\nKendelier<br />\nSchreder<br />\nGE Lighting<br />\nNXP<br />\nSiemens<br />\nPanasonic<br />\nWireless Environment LLC<br />\nBelkin<br />\nCree<br />\nLutron<br />\nLeviton<br />\nCreston<br />\nTelensa<br />\nLC&D<br />\nSunyeah<br />\nKenall<br />\nLithonia Lighting<br />\nAcquitybrands<br />\nColumbia Lighting<br />\nKim Lighting<br />\nEaton<br />\nDigital Lumens<br />\nJuno Lighting<br />\nHitech LED<br />\nLusio Lighting<br />\nSylvania<br />\nOsram<br />\nAutani<br />\nSchneider Electric<br />\nAlera Lighting<br />\nLiteControl<br />\nHubbell<br />\nHoneywell<br />\nRockwell Automation<br />\nSamsung<br />\nCarandini<br />\nILP<br />\nAtla