(865, 'US8902225B2', 'The existing holographic user interface systems project images in a two-dimensional (2-D) space such as against a curtain of air or glass. Such systems may operate as a floating touchscreen when connected to a computer. However, the interaction of a user with these existing systems is limited to only two dimensions, not utilizing the full three-dimensional (3-D) coordinate system.\r\n\r\nTherefore, there is a need for a user interface system that enables the user to interact with a computing system in the 3-D coordinate system.', 'The present invention describes a user interface system for manipulating a holographic image being projected in a three-dimensional (3-D) coordinate system. The user interface system includes at least one sensor, a processor and a projecting unit. \r\n\r\nThe sensor is configured to sense user interaction with the holographic image. On sensing the user interaction, the sensor determines a sensing point position corresponding to the user interaction within the 3-D coordinate system. The coordinate information corresponding to the sensing point position is provided to the processor by the sensor.  Examples of the sensor include a laser sensor, a photo voltaic sensor, a photo electric light sensor and an image sensor. The laser sensor determines the sensing point position using  triangulation and/or quadrilation in the 3-D coordinate system.\r\n\r\nThe processor is configured to correlate the sensed user interaction information, received from the sensor, with the holographic image in the 3-D coordinate system. Based on the correlation, the projecting unit is configured to project an updated holographic image. The updated holographic image is the manipulated version of the holographic image. Examples of the manipulation include twisting, bending, cutting, displacement, and squeezing. \r\n\r\nThe manipulation to be applied on the holographic image is selected by the processor based on at least one indicator. The indicator may be provided by a vocal command, the user interaction or any other input means.  For example, the processor can identify squeezing based on the indicator that the user''s fingers are in a pinching configuration.', '3D Hologram Projection<br/>Holographic Displays<br/>Sensor based User Interaction<br/>Hologram based User Input<br/>Interaction with 3D Holograms<br/>', '3D Hologram Projectors\r\n3D Laser Projectors\r\n3D Glasses\r\nHeads-Up-Displays (HUDs)\r\nTelepresence\r\nGaming Systems\r\nMedical Systems\r\nEducational Tools\r\nHolographic Television and Computer Displays\r\nSmart Phones\r\nEntertainment Systems\r\nVirtual Reality Systems\r\nSimulators\r\nComputer-Aided Design (CAD)\r\nNavigation Systems\r\nHolography based Input Devices', 'Microsoft<br />\nMagic Leap <br />\nOculus (Parent: Facebook)<br />\nAmazon<br />\nApple<br />\nechoPixel <br />\nHologamUSA <br />\nHoloCube <br />\nImmersiveTouch <br />\nIntel <br />\nLeia3D <br />\nOccipital <br />\nProvision<br />\nRealView - Medical Holography  <br />\nVoxiebox <br />\nZebra Imaging <br />\nZSpace Inc <br />\nChristie Digital<br />\nCISCO<br />\nGoogle <br />\nTakee<br />\nH+ Tech<br />\nHP <br />\nHolovect Industries <br />\nHoloxica <br />\nAV Concepts<br />\nEON Reality<br />\nMusion <br />\nTrimble Navigation <br />\nDaqri<br />\nDassault Systems <br />\nDisney <br />\nNettlebox <br />\nNinendo <br />\nSamsung<br />\nSEGA <br />\nSONY  <br />\nVolkswagen<br />\nVirdex<br />\nGE<br />\nKonica Minolta<br />\nMotorola <br />\nNokia <br />\nPanasonic<br />\nPhilips <br />\n4Dpresence <br />\n360BRANDVISION<br />\nCellulon <br />\nGeomagic <br />\nViewSonic <br />\nLG Electronics <br />\nLockheed Martin <br />\nNavdy <br />\nSAP <br />\nSpaceX <br />\nTesla', '<a href="https://www.microsoft.com/microsoft-hololens/en-us">Microsoft - Microsoft HoloLens</a><br/><a href="http://www.magicleap.com/#/home">Magic Leap - Magic Leap</a><br/><a href="https://www.oculus.com/en-us/rift/">Oculus (Parent: Facebook) - Oc