(866, 'US8730165B2', 'The existing holographic user interface systems project images in a two-dimensional (2-D) space such as against a curtain of air or glass. Such systems may operate as a floating touchscreen when connected to a computer. However, the interaction of a user with these existing systems is limited to only two dimensions, not utilizing the full three-dimensional (3-D) coordinate system.\r\n\r\nTherefore, there is a need for a user interface system that enables the user to interact with a computing system in the 3-D coordinate system.', 'The present invention describes a three-dimensional (3-D) user interface system for moving a holographic image from a first location to a second location in a 3-D coordinate system based on user interaction. The 3-D user interface system includes one or more 3-D projectors, sensors and a processor.\r\n\r\nThe 3-D projectors are configured to project the holographic image at the first location in the 3-D coordinate system. When a user interacts with the holographic image, the sensors sense the user interaction. The information corresponding to the user interaction is provided to the processor by the sensors. Examples of the sensors include location sensors, motion sensors, light sensors and sound sensors.\r\n\r\nIn an example, the user interaction may be the movement of the user or one of user''s body parts such as a finger from the first position to the second position. The processor receives the user interaction information and correlates the information with the holographic image based on the 3-D coordinate system. The processor is further configured to provide indications in response to the correlation. Based on the indications, the 3-D projectors project the holographic image at the second location in the 3-D coordinate system.\r\n\r\nFor example, the holographic image may be an image of an input device for a computer. In this case, the indications provided by the processor include input data for the computer.', '